Here's the xUnit equivalent. The key mappings are:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture's `Dispose` |

```csharp
// Fixture handles one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// IClassFixture<T> triggers the fixture lifecycle
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp] — runs before each test
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // Dispose replaces [TearDown] — runs after each test
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **Per-test**: constructor + `IDisposable` replace `[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]`
- **Per-class**: `IClassFixture<T>` replaces `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]` — xUnit creates one `DatabaseFixture` instance shared across all tests
- The fixture is injected via the constructor but you don't need to use it unless it exposes shared state
- Assertions change: `Is.EqualTo(x)` → `Assert.Equal(x, actual)`, `Is.Not.Null` → `Assert.NotNull`
